253  /*
254  [ENUM]
255  [
256  [DESCRIPTION]
257  These output types are used with System::setOutput / System::getOutput, to choose which output method to use.
258 
259  [REMARKS]
260  To pass information to the driver when initializing fmod use the *extradriverdata* parameter in System::init for the following reasons.
261 
262  - FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_WAVWRITER - extradriverdata is a pointer to a char * file name that the wav writer will output to.
263  - FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_WAVWRITER_NRT - extradriverdata is a pointer to a char * file name that the wav writer will output to.
264  - FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_DSOUND - extradriverdata is cast to a HWND type, so that FMOD can set the focus on the audio for a particular window.
265  - FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_PS3 - extradriverdata is a pointer to a FMOD_PS3_EXTRADRIVERDATA struct. This can be found in fmodps3.h.
266  - FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_XBOX360 - extradriverdata is a pointer to a FMOD_360_EXTRADRIVERDATA struct. This can be found in fmodxbox360.h.
267 
268  Currently these are the only FMOD drivers that take extra information. Other unknown plugins may have different requirements.
269 
270  Note! If FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_WAVWRITER_NRT or FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_NOSOUND_NRT are used, and if the System::update function is being called
271  very quickly (ie for a non realtime decode) it may be being called too quickly for the FMOD streamer thread to respond to.
272  The result will be a skipping/stuttering output in the captured audio.
273 
274  To remedy this, disable the FMOD streamer thread, and use FMOD_INIT_STREAM_FROM_UPDATE to avoid skipping in the output stream,
275  as it will lock the mixer and the streamer together in the same thread.
276 
277  [SEE_ALSO]
278  System::setOutput
279  System::getOutput
280  System::setSoftwareFormat
281  System::getSoftwareFormat
282  System::init
283  System::update
284  FMOD_INITFLAGS
285  ]
286  */

405  /*
406  [ENUM]
407  [
408  [DESCRIPTION]
409  These are speaker types defined for use with the System::setSoftwareFormat command.
410 
411  [REMARKS]
412  Note below the phrase 'sound channels' is used. These are the subchannels inside a sound, they are not related and
413  have nothing to do with the FMOD class "Channel".<br>
414  For example a mono sound has 1 sound channel, a stereo sound has 2 sound channels, and an AC3 or 6 channel wav file have 6 "sound channels".<br>
415  <br>
416  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_RAW<br>
417  ---------------------<br>
418  This mode is for output devices that are not specifically mono/stereo/quad/surround/5.1 or 7.1, but are multichannel.<br>
419  Use System::setSoftwareFormat to specify the number of speakers you want to address, otherwise it will default to 2 (stereo).<br>
420  Sound channels map to speakers sequentially, so a mono sound maps to output speaker 0, stereo sound maps to output speaker 0 & 1.<br>
421  The user assumes knowledge of the speaker order. FMOD_SPEAKER enumerations may not apply, so raw channel indices should be used.<br>
422  Multichannel sounds map input channels to output channels 1:1. <br>
423  Channel::setPan and Channel::setPanLevels do not work.<br>
424  Speaker levels must be manually set with Channel::setPanMatrix.<br>
425  <br>
426  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_MONO<br>
427  ---------------------<br>
428  This mode is for a 1 speaker arrangement.<br>
429  Panning does not work in this speaker mode.<br>
430  Mono, stereo and multichannel sounds have each sound channel played on the one speaker unity.<br>
431  Mix behavior for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setPanMatrix.<br>
432  Channel::setPanLevels does not work.<br>
433  <br>
434  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_STEREO<br>
435  -----------------------<br>
436  This mode is for 2 speaker arrangements that have a left and right speaker.<br>
437  <li>Mono sounds default to an even distribution between left and right. They can be panned with Channel::setPan.<br>
438  <li>Stereo sounds default to the middle, or full left in the left speaker and full right in the right speaker.
439  <li>They can be cross faded with Channel::setPan.<br>
440  <li>Multichannel sounds have each sound channel played on each speaker at unity.<br>
441  <li>Mix behavior for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setPanMatrix.<br>
442  <li>Channel::setPanLevels works but only front left and right parameters are used, the rest are ignored.<br>
443  <br>
444  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_QUAD<br>
445  ------------------------<br>
446  This mode is for 4 speaker arrangements that have a front left, front right, surround left and a surround right speaker.<br>
447  <li>Mono sounds default to an even distribution between front left and front right. They can be panned with Channel::setPan.<br>
448  <li>Stereo sounds default to the left sound channel played on the front left, and the right sound channel played on the front right.<br>
449  <li>They can be cross faded with Channel::setPan.<br>
450  <li>Multichannel sounds default to all of their sound channels being played on each speaker in order of input.<br>
451  <li>Mix behavior for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setPanMatrix.<br>
452  <li>Channel::setPanLevels works but rear left, rear right, center and lfe are ignored.<br>
453  <br>
454  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_SURROUND<br>
455  ------------------------<br>
456  This mode is for 5 speaker arrangements that have a left/right/center/surround left/surround right.<br>
457  <li>Mono sounds default to the center speaker. They can be panned with Channel::setPan.<br>
458  <li>Stereo sounds default to the left sound channel played on the front left, and the right sound channel played on the front right.
459  <li>They can be cross faded with Channel::setPan.<br>
460  <li>Multichannel sounds default to all of their sound channels being played on each speaker in order of input.
461  <li>Mix behavior for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setPanMatrix.<br>
462  <li>Channel::setPanLevels works but rear left / rear right are ignored.<br>
463  <br>
464  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_5POINT1<br>
465  ---------------------------------------------------------<br>
466  This mode is for 5.1 speaker arrangements that have a left/right/center/surround left/surround right and a subwoofer speaker.<br>
467  <li>Mono sounds default to the center speaker. They can be panned with Channel::setPan.<br>
468  <li>Stereo sounds default to the left sound channel played on the front left, and the right sound channel played on the front right.
469  <li>They can be cross faded with Channel::setPan.<br>
470  <li>Multichannel sounds default to all of their sound channels being played on each speaker in order of input.
471  <li>Mix behavior for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setPanMatrix.<br>
472  <li>Channel::setPanLevels works but rear left / rear right are ignored.<br>
473  <br>
474  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_7POINT1<br>
475  ------------------------<br>
476  This mode is for 7.1 speaker arrangements that have a left/right/center/surround left/surround right/rear left/rear right
477  and a subwoofer speaker.<br>
478  <li>Mono sounds default to the center speaker. They can be panned with Channel::setPan.<br>
479  <li>Stereo sounds default to the left sound channel played on the front left, and the right sound channel played on the front right.
480  <li>They can be cross faded with Channel::setPan.<br>
481  <li>Multichannel sounds default to all of their sound channels being played on each speaker in order of input.
482  <li>Mix behavior for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setPanMatrix.<br>
483  <li>Channel::setPanLevels works and every parameter is used to set the balance of a sound in any speaker.<br>
484  <br>
485 
486  [SEE_ALSO]
487  System::setSoftwareFormat
488  System::getSoftwareFormat
489  DSP::setChannelFormat
490  ]
491  */

758  /*
759  [DEFINE]
760  [
761  [NAME]
762  FMOD_MODE
763 
764  [DESCRIPTION]
765  Sound description bitfields, bitwise OR them together for loading and describing sounds.
766 
767  [REMARKS]
768  By default a sound will open as a static sound that is decompressed fully into memory to PCM. (ie equivalent of FMOD_CREATESAMPLE)<br>
769  To have a sound stream instead, use FMOD_CREATESTREAM, or use the wrapper function System::createStream.<br>
770  Some opening modes (ie FMOD_OPENUSER, FMOD_OPENMEMORY, FMOD_OPENMEMORY_POINT, FMOD_OPENRAW) will need extra information.<br>
771  This can be provided using the FMOD_CREATESOUNDEXINFO structure.
772  <br>
773  Specifying FMOD_OPENMEMORY_POINT will POINT to your memory rather allocating its own sound buffers and duplicating it internally.<br>
774  <b><u>This means you cannot free the memory while FMOD is using it, until after Sound::release is called.</b></u>
775  With FMOD_OPENMEMORY_POINT, for PCM formats, only WAV, FSB, and RAW are supported. For compressed formats, only those formats supported by FMOD_CREATECOMPRESSEDSAMPLE are supported.<br>
776  With FMOD_OPENMEMORY_POINT and FMOD_OPENRAW or PCM, if using them together, note that you must pad the data on each side by 16 bytes. This is so fmod can modify the ends of the data for looping/interpolation/mixing purposes. If a wav file, you will need to insert silence, and then reset loop points to stop the playback from playing that silence.<br>
777  <br>
778  <b>Xbox 360 memory</b> On Xbox 360 Specifying FMOD_OPENMEMORY_POINT to a virtual memory address will cause FMOD_ERR_INVALID_ADDRESS
779  to be returned. Use physical memory only for this functionality.<br>
780  <br>
781  FMOD_LOWMEM is used on a sound if you want to minimize the memory overhead, by having FMOD not allocate memory for certain
782  features that are not likely to be used in a game environment. These are :<br>
783  1. Sound::getName functionality is removed. 256 bytes per sound is saved.<br>
784 
785  [SEE_ALSO]
786  System::createSound
787  System::createStream
788  Sound::setMode
789  Sound::getMode
790  Channel::setMode
791  Channel::getMode
792  Sound::set3DCustomRolloff
793  Channel::set3DCustomRolloff
794  Sound::getOpenState

1044  #region wrapperinternal
1045  [StructLayout(LayoutKind.Sequential)]
1046  public struct StringWrapper
1047  {
1048  IntPtr nativeUtf8Ptr;
1049 
1050  public static implicit operator string(StringWrapper fstring)
1051  {
1052  if (fstring.nativeUtf8Ptr == IntPtr.Zero)
1053  {
1054  return "";
1055  }
1056 
1057  int strlen = 0;
1058  while (Marshal.ReadByte(fstring.nativeUtf8Ptr, strlen) != 0)
1059  {
1060  strlen++;
1061  }
1062  if (strlen > 0)
1063  {
1064  byte[] bytes = new byte[strlen];
1065  Marshal.Copy(fstring.nativeUtf8Ptr, bytes, 0, strlen);
1066  return Encoding.UTF8.GetString(bytes, 0, strlen);
1067  }
1068  else
1069  {
1070  return "";
1071  }
1072  }
1073  }

1130  /*
1131  [ENUM]
1132  [
1133  [DESCRIPTION]
1134  List of connection types between 2 DSP nodes.
1135 
1136  [REMARKS]
1137  FMOD_DSP_CONNECTION_TYPE_STANDARD<br>
1138  ----------------------------------<br>
1139  Default DSPConnection type. Audio is mixed from the input to the output DSP's audible buffer, meaning it will be part of the audible signal. A standard connection will execute its input DSP if it has not been executed before.<br>
1140  <br>
1141  FMOD_DSP_CONNECTION_TYPE_SIDECHAIN<br>
1142  ----------------------------------<br>
1143  Sidechain DSPConnection type. Audio is mixed from the input to the output DSP's sidechain buffer, meaning it will NOT be part of the audible signal. A sidechain connection will execute its input DSP if it has not been executed before.<br>
1144  The purpose of the seperate sidechain buffer in a DSP, is so that the DSP effect can privately access for analysis purposes. An example of use in this case, could be a compressor which analyzes the signal, to control its own effect parameters (ie a compression level or gain).<br>
1145  <br>
1146  For the effect developer, to accept sidechain data, the sidechain data will appear in the FMOD_DSP_STATE struct which is passed into the read callback of a DSP unit.<br>
1147  FMOD_DSP_STATE::sidechaindata and FMOD_DSP::sidechainchannels will hold the mixed result of any sidechain data flowing into it.<br>
1148  <br>
1149  FMOD_DSP_CONNECTION_TYPE_SEND<br>
1150  -----------------------------<br>
1151  Send DSPConnection type. Audio is mixed from the input to the output DSP's audible buffer, meaning it will be part of the audible signal. A send connection will NOT execute its input DSP if it has not been executed before.<br>
1152  A send connection will only read what exists at the input's buffer at the time of executing the output DSP unit (which can be considered the 'return')<br>
1153  <br>
1154  FMOD_DSP_CONNECTION_TYPE_SEND_SIDECHAIN<br>
1155  ---------------------------------------<br>
1156  Send sidechain DSPConnection type. Audio is mixed from the input to the output DSP's sidechain buffer, meaning it will NOT be part of the audible signal. A send sidechain connection will NOT execute its input DSP if it has not been executed before.<br>
1157  A send sidechain connection will only read what exists at the input's buffer at the time of executing the output DSP unit (which can be considered the 'sidechain return').
1158  <br>
1159  For the effect developer, to accept sidechain data, the sidechain data will appear in the FMOD_DSP_STATE struct which is passed into the read callback of a DSP unit.<br>
1160  FMOD_DSP_STATE::sidechaindata and FMOD_DSP::sidechainchannels will hold the mixed result of any sidechain data flowing into it.
1161 
1162  [SEE_ALSO]
1163  DSP::addInput
1164  DSPConnection::getType
1165  ]
1166  */
1167  public enum DSPCONNECTION_TYPE : int
1168  {
1169  STANDARD, /* Default connection type. Audio is mixed from the input to the output DSP's audible buffer. */
1170  SIDECHAIN, /* Sidechain connection type. Audio is mixed from the input to the output DSP's sidechain buffer. */
1171  SEND, /* Send connection type. Audio is mixed from the input to the output DSP's audible buffer, but the input is NOT executed, only copied from. A standard connection or sidechain needs to make an input execute to generate data. */
1172  SEND_SIDECHAIN, /* Send sidechain connection type. Audio is mixed from the input to the output DSP's sidechain buffer, but the input is NOT executed, only copied from. A standard connection or sidechain needs to make an input execute to generate data. */
1173 
1174  MAX, /* Maximum number of DSP connection types supported. */
1175  }

1314  /*
1315  [STRUCTURE]
1316  [
1317  [DESCRIPTION]
1318  Use this structure with System::createSound when more control is needed over loading.
1319  The possible reasons to use this with System::createSound are:
1320 
1321  - Loading a file from memory.
1322  - Loading a file from within another larger (possibly wad/pak) file, by giving the loader an offset and length.
1323  - To create a user created / non file based sound.
1324  - To specify a starting subsound to seek to within a multi-sample sounds (ie FSB/DLS) when created as a stream.
1325  - To specify which subsounds to load for multi-sample sounds (ie FSB/DLS) so that memory is saved and only a subset is actually loaded/read from disk.
1326  - To specify 'piggyback' read and seek callbacks for capture of sound data as fmod reads and decodes it. Useful for ripping decoded PCM data from sounds as they are loaded / played.
1327  - To specify a MIDI DLS sample set file to load when opening a MIDI file.
1328 
1329  See below on what members to fill for each of the above types of sound you want to create.
1330 
1331  [REMARKS]
1332  This structure is optional! Specify 0 or NULL in System::createSound if you don't need it!
1333 
1334  <u>Loading a file from memory.</u>
1335 
1336  - Create the sound using the FMOD_OPENMEMORY flag.
1337  - Mandatory. Specify 'length' for the size of the memory block in bytes.
1338  - Other flags are optional.
1339 
1340  <u>Loading a file from within another larger (possibly wad/pak) file, by giving the loader an offset and length.</u>
1341 
1342  - Mandatory. Specify 'fileoffset' and 'length'.
1343  - Other flags are optional.
1344 
1345  <u>To create a user created / non file based sound.</u>
1346 
1347  - Create the sound using the FMOD_OPENUSER flag.
1348  - Mandatory. Specify 'defaultfrequency, 'numchannels' and 'format'.
1349  - Other flags are optional.
1350 
1351  <u>To specify a starting subsound to seek to and flush with, within a multi-sample stream (ie FSB/DLS).</u>
1352 
1353  - Mandatory. Specify 'initialsubsound'.
1354 
1355  <u>To specify which subsounds to load for multi-sample sounds (ie FSB/DLS) so that memory is saved and only a subset is actually loaded/read from disk.</u>
1356 
1357  - Mandatory. Specify 'inclusionlist' and 'inclusionlistnum'.
1358 
1359  <u>To specify 'piggyback' read and seek callbacks for capture of sound data as fmod reads and decodes it. Useful for ripping decoded PCM data from sounds as they are loaded / played.</u>
1360 
1361  - Mandatory. Specify 'pcmreadcallback' and 'pcmseekcallback'.
1362 
1363  <u>To specify a MIDI DLS sample set file to load when opening a MIDI file.</u>
1364 
1365  - Mandatory. Specify 'dlsname'.
1366 
1367  Setting the 'decodebuffersize' is for cpu intensive codecs that may be causing stuttering, not file intensive codecs (ie those from CD or netstreams) which are normally
1368  altered with System::setStreamBufferSize. As an example of cpu intensive codecs, an mp3 file will take more cpu to decode than a PCM wav file.
1369 
1370  If you have a stuttering effect, then it is using more cpu than the decode buffer playback rate can keep up with. Increasing the decode buffersize will most likely solve this problem.
1371 
1372  FSB codec. If inclusionlist and numsubsounds are used together, this will trigger a special mode where subsounds are shuffled down to save memory. (useful for large FSB
1373  files where you only want to load 1 sound). There will be no gaps, ie no null subsounds. As an example, if there are 10,000 subsounds and there is an inclusionlist with only 1 entry,
1374  and numsubsounds = 1, then subsound 0 will be that entry, and there will only be the memory allocated for 1 subsound. Previously there would still be 10,000 subsound pointers and other
1375  associated codec entries allocated along with it multiplied by 10,000.
